> "The Son of God became man so that we might become God."
> — St. Athanasius of Alexandria, *On the Incarnation*, §54 (c. AD 318)

The divinity of Jesus Christ is the non-negotiable center of Christian faith. Every other doctrine — the Atonement, the sacraments, the authority of the Church, the resurrection of the body — depends on its truth. If Jesus is not God, his death is the tragedy of a good man; if he is God, it is the redemption of the world. The New Testament, the earliest Christian writers, and the first Ecumenical Councils all converge on the same answer: the man from Nazareth is the eternal Son of the Father, the second Person of the Trinity, who took on human flesh for our salvation.

---

## The I AM Sayings: Jesus and the Divine Name

### John 8:58 — Before Abraham Was, I AM

The most direct claim Jesus makes to divine identity is found in John 8:58: *"Amen, amen, I say to you, before Abraham came to be, I AM."* The construction is not merely a claim to pre-existence — it is a deliberate invocation of the divine name revealed to Moses at the burning bush: *"I AM WHO AM"* (Exodus 3:14). The audience's response is unambiguous: *"So they picked up stones to throw at him"* (John 8:59). They understood him to be claiming identity with the God of Israel, and they responded with the prescribed penalty for blasphemy under Mosaic law (Leviticus 24:16). Jesus did not retreat from the claim.

### John 10:30 — The Father and I Are One

*"The Father and I are one"* (John 10:30). Again the response is immediate: *"The Jews again picked up rocks to stone him"* (John 10:31), explaining: *"You, a man, are making yourself God"* (John 10:33). Jesus's opponents understood him perfectly. His subsequent argument does not deny the claim — it defends the propriety of his making it.

### John 20:28 — Thomas's Confession

After the Resurrection, the apostle Thomas addresses the risen Christ: *"My Lord and my God!"* (John 20:28). This is the most explicit confession of Christ's divinity in the New Testament. In Jewish monotheistic context, addressing any being other than the God of Israel as "my God" is blasphemy. Jesus does not correct Thomas. Instead, he pronounces a blessing on all who believe without having seen. Thomas's confession is held up as the model of resurrection faith.

---

## Positive Biblical Evidence

### John 1:1 — The Pre-existent Word

*"In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God"* (John 1:1, NABRE). The opening verse of John's Gospel deliberately echoes Genesis 1:1, placing the Word at the origin of all creation. Three propositions are stated: the Word existed before all things; the Word was in an eternal relationship with God; the Word *was* God. The Word is then identified as Jesus Christ (John 1:14, 1:17). This passage leaves no exegetical space for a merely elevated creature.

### Colossians 2:9 — The Fullness of Deity

*"For in him dwells the whole fullness of the deity bodily"* (Colossians 2:9, NABRE). Paul uses *theotētos* — "deity," "Godhead" — the fullest Greek term for divine nature. The word *plērōma* ("fullness") indicates totality, not partial participation. The adverb *sōmatikōs* ("bodily") insists on the reality of the Incarnation. Christ is not God-like or god-inspired; the entire divine nature dwells in him in bodily form.

### Philippians 2:6–7 — The Form of God

*"Who, though he was in the form of God, did not regard equality with God something to be grasped. Rather, he emptied himself, taking the form of a slave, coming in human likeness"* (Philippians 2:6–7, NABRE). The Greek *morphē theou* ("form of God") denotes the actual divine nature, not merely an appearance. The movement described — from divine equality to human lowliness — presupposes a pre-existent divine subject who freely chose Incarnation.

### Hebrews 1:8 — The Son Addressed as God

*"But of the Son he says: 'Your throne, O God, stands forever and ever'"* (Hebrews 1:8, NABRE). The Father addresses the Son directly as "God" — applying a messianic psalm (Psalm 45) to Christ. This direct divine address is one of the most theologically pregnant texts in the New Testament.

### Revelation 22:13 — Alpha and Omega

*"I am the Alpha and the Omega, the first and the last, the beginning and the end"* (Revelation 22:13, NABRE). This title, claimed by God himself in Isaiah 44:6 and Revelation 1:8, is here spoken by the risen Christ. The attribution of this uniquely divine self-description to Jesus identifies him with the God of the Old Testament.

---

## The Core Theological Distinction: The Hypostatic Union

The Council of Chalcedon (451 AD) defined the orthodox doctrine of the Incarnation with precision:

> *"We confess one and the same Son, our Lord Jesus Christ, the same perfect in Godhead and also perfect in manhood; truly God and truly man... to be acknowledged in two natures, without confusion, without change, without division, without separation."*

This formulation rules out four historical heresies simultaneously:

| Heresy | Error | Chalcedonian Refutation |
|--------|-------|------------------------|
| **Arianism** | Christ is a creature, not truly God | *"Perfect in Godhead... truly God"* |
| **Apollinarianism** | Christ had no human mind/soul | *"Perfect in manhood... truly man"* |
| **Nestorianism** | Christ is two persons | *"One and the same Son"* |
| **Monophysitism** | Christ has only one (divine) nature | *"In two natures"* |

The **hypostatic union** — one divine Person, two complete natures — is the precise formulation that does justice to the full witness of Scripture: the texts that affirm Christ's divinity and the texts that affirm his genuine humanity, his suffering, his ignorance in his human nature, his growth and development.

---

## Church Fathers

> "There is one Physician who is both flesh and spirit, born and unborn, God in man, true life in death, both of Mary and of God — Jesus Christ our Lord."
> — St. Ignatius of Antioch, *Letter to the Ephesians*, AD 107

Ignatius, writing barely a decade after the death of the Apostle John, uses language that explicitly affirms both the divinity and humanity of Christ. There is no gap between the apostolic generation and the confession that Jesus is God.

> "Jesus Christ is the only proper Son who has been begotten by God, being His Word and first-begotten, and power; and becoming man according to His will, He taught us these things."
> — St. Justin Martyr, *First Apology*, 63 (c. AD 155)

Justin, the first great Christian philosopher, identifies Jesus with the eternal Logos of God — not a second god, but the Word through whom the one God created and governs all things, and who became man for our salvation.

> "For this is why the Word became man, and the Son of God became the Son of man: so that man, by entering into communion with the Word and thus receiving divine sonship, might become a son of God."
> — St. Irenaeus of Lyon, *Against Heresies*, III.19.1 (c. AD 180)

Irenaeus's doctrine of **recapitulation** grounds salvation itself in the Incarnation: Christ assumes human nature in order to restore and elevate it. If Christ were not truly God, the restoration would be impossible; if he were not truly man, the restoration would not reach us.

> "The Son of God became man so that we might become God."
> — St. Athanasius of Alexandria, *On the Incarnation*, §54 (c. AD 318)

Athanasius's famous formula — *"God became man that man might become God"* — captures the entire logic of salvation. Divinization (*theōsis*) requires a Savior who is genuinely divine. An exalted creature cannot share divine life with us; only God can. This is why Athanasius spent seventeen years in exile rather than compromise the *homoousios*.

---

## Ecumenical Council: Council of Nicaea (325 AD)

The First Ecumenical Council was called by Emperor Constantine to resolve the Arian controversy. Arius had taught that the Son was the first and greatest creature — *"there was a time when he was not."* Against this, the Council defined:

> *"We believe in one Lord, Jesus Christ, the Son of God, begotten from the Father, only-begotten, that is, from the substance of the Father, God from God, Light from Light, true God from true God, begotten not made,* **of one substance** (homoousios) *with the Father."*

The word *homoousios* — "of the same substance" — was the precise term Arianism could not accept. It affirms that the Son does not merely resemble the Father or participate in his divinity; he *is* divine in the same sense the Father is divine. Every subsequent Christological definition (Constantinople I, Ephesus, Chalcedon) builds on this Nicene foundation.

---

