## Common Objections

**"Jesus never explicitly said 'I am God — worship me.'"**

Jesus communicated his divine identity through actions and claims that his contemporaries recognized as divine claims: forgiving sins (a prerogative of God alone — Mark 2:7), accepting worship without rebuke (Matthew 28:17, John 20:28), claiming authority over the Sabbath (Mark 2:28), and applying the divine name "I AM" to himself (John 8:58). In Jewish context, these were unambiguous claims to divinity. The demand for an explicit modern-style declaration ignores how Jewish theological communication worked.

**"The disciples invented Christ's divinity after the Resurrection."**

St. Ignatius of Antioch writes of Christ's divinity in AD 107 — within living memory of the apostles and before a single New Testament book had wide circulation as "Scripture." The creedal formula in 1 Corinthians 15:3–8, which Paul says he "received" (suggesting it predates his letter by years), affirms the Resurrection as a historical event, not a later theological invention. The Nicene definition did not *create* the belief; it *defined* a belief already universally held.

**"Arius was a sincere Christian — couldn't he be right?"**

Arius was sincere, but sincerity is not truth. His position creates an insoluble soteriological problem: if Christ is a creature, no matter how exalted, his death is not an infinite atonement, and his gift of "divine life" is not the genuine divine life. The Nicene fathers recognized that Arianism does not merely adjust one doctrine — it collapses the entire structure of Christian salvation. This is why 318 bishops condemned it, and why Athanasius spent his life defending the alternative.

**"Isn't the Trinity just a later Greek philosophical invention?"**

The doctrine of the Trinity is a *theological formulation* using available philosophical vocabulary to express what the New Testament reveals: that the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit are each divine, and yet God is one. The vocabulary is Greek; the content is scriptural. The Council of Nicaea did not impose Hellenistic philosophy on a non-Greek Gospel — it used the philosophical precision available to say clearly what the Gospel teaches: that the Son is not a secondary deity but *homoousios*, of the same divine substance as the Father.

---

The divinity of Jesus Christ is not a later development, a philosophical imposition, or a well-intentioned exaggeration of a great teacher's legacy. It is the explicit claim of the New Testament, the universal confession of the earliest Christian communities from Antioch to Rome, and the formally defined doctrine of the first Ecumenical Council. At its heart is a truth so simple and so staggering that it has never ceased to provoke: the man who died on a Roman cross was the eternal God through whom all things were made — and he died to make us his.
